\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. R. groenlandicus} (Ostenf.) Chab., {\i Bull. Herb. Boiss.}{\b  7}: 511 (1899). Stem up to 30 cm, simple or slightly branched, stout, hairy on 2 opposite sides. Leaves rather fleshy, coarsely dentate, with patent, acute teeth, bright yellowish-green. Bracts exceeding the calyx, triangular, with long, patent teeth, glabrous or puberulent. Calyx glabrous or puberulent. Corolla c. 15 mm; tube straight; throat open. 2n = 22. {\i  N. Europe, southwards to} c. 60°{\i  N. in the mountains of Norway.} Fa Fe Is No Rs (N) Su.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. R. minor} L.,{\i  Amoen. Acad.}{\b  3}: 54 (1756) ({\i Alectorolophus minor} (L.) Wimmer & Grab.; incl. {\i R. borealis} (Sterneck) Druce, {\i R. rusticulus }(Chab.) Druce,{\i  R. nigricans} Meinsh.). Stem 5-50 cm, sometimes with black streaks. Leaves (2-)5-15 mm wide, ovate-oblong to linear-lanceolate, crenate-serrate (the uppermost sometimes dentate), rather dark green. Bracts longer than to slightly shorter than calyx, triangular, glabrous or somewhat scabrid. Calyx glabrous or puberulent. Corolla 13-15 mm; tube straight; throat more or less open. 2n = 22.{\i  Most of Europe, but rare in the Mediterranean region.} All except Az Bl Co Cr Sa Sb Si Tu.
