\pard\f0\fs28  In addition to the usual ecotypic variation this species shows much variation in other characters. Plants with puberulent calyx are commonest in northern areas or at high altitudes, and are sometimes separated as {\b R. borealis} (Sterneck) Druce,{\i  Ann. Scott. Nat. Hist.}{\b  1901}: 178 (1901). This character, however, shows little correlation with others, and as mixed populations of plants, some with pubescent and some with glabrous calyx, are common (as are, in some regions, plants with calyx puberulent when young but later glabrescent), taxonomic separation does not seem to be possible.
